SIMPLE: such
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Such
<hw>Such</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>such</ets>,
<ets>sich</ets>, <ets>sech</ets>, <ets>sik</ets>, <ets>swich</ets>,
<ets>swilch</ets>, <ets>swulch</ets>, <ets>swilc</ets>,
<ets>swulc</ets>, AS. <ets>swelc</ets>, <ets>swilc</ets>,
<ets>swylc</ets>; akin to OFries. <ets>selik</ets>, D. <ets>zulk</ets>,
OS. <ets>sulic</ets>, OHG. <ets>sulih</ets>, <ets>solih</ets>, G.
<ets>solch</ets>, Icel. <ets>sl⟦imac⟧kr</ets>, OSw. <ets>salik</ets>,
Sw. <ets>slik</ets>, Dan. <ets>slig</ets>, Goth. <ets>swaleiks</ets>;
originally meaning, so shaped. ⟦root⟧192. See <er>So</er>,
<er>Like</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Which</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Of that kind; of the like kind; like; resembling; similar; <as>as,
we never saw <ex>such</ex> a day</as>; -- followed by <xex>that</xex> or
<xex>as</xex> introducing the word or proposition which defines the
similarity, or the standard of comparison; <as>as, the books are not
<ex>such</ex> that I can recommend them, or, not <ex>such</ex> as I can
recommend; these apples are not <ex>such</ex> as those we saw yesterday;
give your children <ex>such</ex> precepts as tend to make them
better</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And in his time <qex>such</qex> a conqueror⟦br⟧
That greater was there none under the sun.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His misery was <qex>such</qex> that none of the bystanders could
refrain from weeping.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The indefinite article <xex>a</xex> or <xex>an</xex>
never precedes <xex>such</xex>, but is placed between it and the noun to
which it refers; as, <xex>such a</xex> man; <xex>such an</xex> honor.
The indefinite adjective <xex>some</xex>, <xex>several</xex>,
<xex>one</xex>, <xex>few</xex>, <xex>many</xex>, <xex>all</xex>, etc.,
precede <xex>such</xex>; as, one <xex>such</xex> book is enough; all
<xex>such</xex> people ought to be avoided; few <xex>such</xex> ideas
were then held.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having the particular quality or character
specified.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That thou art happy, owe to God;⟦br⟧
That thou continuest <qex>such</qex>, owe to thyself.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The same that; -- with <xex>as</xex>; <as>as, this
was the state of the kingdom at <ex>such</ex> time as the enemy
landed</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧[It] hath <xex>such</xex> senses as we
have.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Certain; -- representing the object as already
particularized in terms which are not mentioned.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In rushed one and tells him <qex>such</qex> a knight⟦br⟧
Is new arrived.</q> <rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To-day or to-morrow we will go into <qex>such</qex> a city, and
continue there a year.</q> <rj><qau>James iv. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Such</xex> is used pronominally. ⟦ldquo⟧He was the
father of <xex>such</xex> as dwell in tents.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Gen. iv.
20.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Such</xex> as I are free in spirit when our limbs
are chained.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir W. Scott.</au> <xex>Such</xex> is also used
before adjectives joined to substantives; as, the fleet encountered
<xex>such</xex> a terrible storm that it put back. ⟦ldquo⟧Everything was
managed with so much care, and <xex>such</xex> excellent order was
observed.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>De Foe.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Temple sprung from a family which . . . long after his death
produced so many eminent men, and formed <qex>such</qex> distinguished
alliances, that, etc.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><xex>Such</xex> is used emphatically, without the correlative.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now will he be mocking:⟦br⟧
I shall have <qex>such</qex> a life.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><xex>Such</xex> was formerly used with numerals in the sense of
<xex>times as much</xex> or <xex>as many</xex>; as, <xex>such ten</xex>,
or ten times as many.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Such and such</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Such
or such</b></col></mcol>, <cd>certain; some; -- used to represent the
object indefinitely, as already particularized in one way or another, or
as being of one kind or another.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧In <xex>such and such</xex>
a place shall be my camp.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>2 Kings vi. 8.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧Sovereign authority may enact a law commanding <xex>such and
such</xex> an action.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>South.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>Such
like</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Such character</b></col></mcol>,
<cd>of the like kind.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And many other <qex>such like</qex> things ye do.</q>
<rj><qau>Mark vii. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suchospondylous</ent>⟦br⟧
